The paper investigates k-submodular functions, which are a natural family of discrete functions. This suggests that the paper may belong to the Discrete Mathematics (cs.DM) or Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-categories. The paper also generalizes the Min-Max-Theorem for submodular and bisubmodular functions, which suggests that it may belong to the Game Theory (cs.GT) or Computational Complexity (cs.CC) sub-categories. Finally, the paper involves optimization and polyhedra, which suggests that it may belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category.
